The start symbol S can only expand in one of two ways:

1. S → NT62 NT56  
2. S → NT17 NT42

Case 2 is impossible for the given string, because NT42 can only yield the single terminal t62 or t11, so whichever side of the split it occupies the string would have to end with t62 or t11 – the provided string ends with t51.

Hence we must use S → NT62 NT56, and therefore the very first terminal of any derived string must come from the first symbol generated by NT62.

NT62 has only two possible productions:

a. NT62 → NT3 NT64  
b. NT62 → NT63 NT46

For (a) the first terminal comes from NT3.  
NT3 can expand only as

• NT3 → 't68'               (gives first terminal t68)  
• NT3 → NT66 NT62          (gives first terminal from NT66)  
• NT3 → NT70 NT64          (gives first terminal from NT70)

NT66 can only produce t30, t3, t1 or t28; NT70 can only produce t32 or t95. None of these are t51, so the production chain starting with NT3 can never place t51 at the beginning of the sentence.

For (b) the first terminal comes from NT63.  
NT63 can only yield t86, t42, t21, t31 or t56 – again, never t51.

Therefore, regardless of which production sequence is chosen, any string generated by the grammar must begin with one of

t68, t30, t3, t1, t28, t32, t95, t86, t42, t21, t31 or t56

and can never begin with t51.  
Because the given string begins with t51, it cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

To generate the string the start symbol must use one of its two productions:

1. S → NT17 NT42  
   NT42 produces the single terminal t62, which would therefore have to be the very last token of the whole string.  
   The given string ends with t72, not t62, so this alternative is impossible.

2. S → NT62 NT56  

   • Every derivation of NT62 eventually reaches one of the following forms (the only two alternatives it possesses):
         NT62 → NT3 NT64  
         NT62 → NT63 NT46  

   • NT64 is a fixed one-token non-terminal:  
         NT64 → t19 | t36  

   • NT46 can be
         NT46 → NT56 NT62 (recursion)  
         NT46 → NT64 NT10 (again introduces NT64)  
         NT46 → t31

   Hence every possible expansion of NT62 must contain at least one of the three terminals  
   t19, t36, or t31.

   Looking through the 40-token string supplied, none of these three tokens occurs.

Since the first production is ruled out and the second production necessarily yields a token that is absent from the string, the grammar cannot generate the given string.

No

The start symbol S has only two possible productions:

1. S → NT62 NT56  
2. S → NT17 NT42

Case 2  
NT42 is a lexical rule: NT42 → 't62'.  
If production (2) were used, the sentence produced by S would necessarily end with the single terminal t62.  
The given string ends with t32, not t62, so production (2) cannot be used.

Case 1  
Therefore S must expand by (1): S → NT62 NT56.  
In any sentence derived this way, every symbol coming from NT56 appears at the extreme right.

NT56 has exactly three binary productions:

a) NT56 → NT71 NT29  
b) NT56 → NT15 NT24  
c) NT56 → NT52 NT74

Hence the last terminal of the whole sentence must be produced by one of  
NT29, NT24 or NT74.

• NT29 → 't94' | 't30'  
• NT24 → 't77'  
• NT74 → 't9' | 't49' | 't71'

Consequently, the only terminals that can finish a sentence generated by S → NT62 NT56 are

t30, t94, t77, t9, t49 or t71.

The given string finishes with t32, which is not among those six possibilities.  
Therefore no derivation for the string can end in NT56, and production (1) is impossible.

Since both alternatives for S are impossible, the grammar cannot generate the supplied string.
